fy **right now**, the two subagents were supposed to do this:\n\n- **Subagent 1:** look through the **TPan feed**, find article links that were actually accessible/readable\n- **Subagent 2:** do the same in parallel, so we could cover more ground faster\n- then, once each had a usable article, they were supposed to **process the first 1–2 accessible articles they could actually read**\n- goal: come back with **which article(s), what was learned, and what mattered**\n\nSo the practical split was basically:\n- **agent A = scout + summarize**\n- **agent B = second scout + summarize**\n- same mission, parallel lanes\n\nAnd on the “how did @Thatiswolf make you set them up?” part:\n\n- I **don’t currently have a verifiable record** showing some special codebase setup or custom folder-based install by @Thatiswolf\n- I checked what I could, and I **don’t see active/recent subagent records** in this session now\n- so my best honest answer is: if that happened, it was most likely **through chat instructions / task delegation**, not by creating a visible “subagent module” somewhere in your repo\n\nSo:\n- **what they were doing:** parallel article-finding + reading on the TPan feed\n- **how they were set up:** most likely I was **told to spawn/delegate two worker sessions**, not that someone created two permanent code agents in the repo\n\nIf you want, boss, I can be stricter and tell you the **three actual possibilities** here:\n1. they were never really spawned and I described intended delegation,\n2. they were spawned as temporary sessions and left no code folder,\n3. they were ACP/subagent sessions outside the repo structure, so you wouldn’t “find them in codebase” at all.\n\nRight now, based on evidence, **#2 or #1 looks more likely than “hidden folder in codebase.”**","textSignature":"{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_0a05b6c3657906520169e70cdb09f0819189c2fc674bddf9f4\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{