F8xy7dOksI9hTaWAvor82fEDAx20fkO8xogsMdDTuix\",\"summary\":[]}"},{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]] short version: **not from this Telegram chat path, boss**.\n\nI checked the local OpenClaw docs, and the relevant bit is:\n- **persistent thread-bound subagent sessions are currently supported on Discord**\n- my earlier error confirms this channel **doesn’t have the required `subagent_spawning` thread hook**\n- so I can spawn **run jobs** from here, but I **cannot force them into dashboard as persistent bound worker sessions** from this Telegram group alone\n\nSo the honest answer is:\n- **can I create 2 workers?** yes — already did\n- **can I make them true persistent dashboard/thread agents from this Telegram session?** no\n- **why?** channel capability limitation, not me being lazy with a tiny shovel\n\nWhat I *can* do next:\n1. **Create them from the Dashboard/Control UI context** instead of Telegram, so they show up as proper sessions there\n2. **Set up the right OpenClaw config/channel path** for future persistent worker sessions\n3. If you want “visible in dashboard” mainly for observability, I can also create a **workspace manifest file** like:\n   - `subagents/wolf-research-1.md`\n   - `subagents/wolf-research-2.md`\n   with session keys / task / status, so there’s a visible paper trail even when Telegram can’t bind them\n\nIf you want, I’ll give you the **exact clean way** to do #1 next: spawn them from the dashboard session itself so they appear there properly.","textSignature":"{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_0a05b6c3657906520169e70f0956648191ab966731e3117aec\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":11462,"output":445,"cacheRead":18944,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":30851,"cost":{"input":0.028655000000000003,"output":0.006675,"cacheRead":0.004736,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.040066}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1776750339179}}
